{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486973"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"221"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/221"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.86,0.06,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80765"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/221"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4967"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42032"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80765"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting advice about weight management. She reports gradually gaining weight over the past 10 years. She experiences fatigue at the end of each day and has intermittent lower back and knee pain which she attributes to her weight. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her BMI is 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Recent blood tests show normal fasting glucose and lipid profile.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management for weight loss?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bariatric surgery","Intensive lifestyle modification","Very low calorie diet with meal replacements","Weight loss medication","Strict 1200 kcal/day diet"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with obesity (BMI 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E) without significant comorbidities. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntensive lifestyle modification\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line intervention. This should include specific, actionable advice about diet (reducing processed foods and sugary drinks, increasing vegetables and whole grains) and exercise (aiming for 45 minutes of moderate-intensity activity most days). Regular follow-up and referral to allied health practitioners like dietitians can support these changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeight loss medication\u003C/strong\u003E should be reserved for patients who have not had success with loosing weight via lifestyle modification due to risks of side effects and the need for careful monitoring. These medications, such as GLP-1 receptor agonists (e.g., semaglutide), should only be considered in patients with a BMI \u226530 kg/m\u00b2 or \u226527 kg/m\u00b2 with weight-related comorbidities, as per clinical guidelines. They should be used in conjunction with ongoing lifestyle interventions rather than as a standalone treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBariatric surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for patients with BMI \u226535 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E regardless of comorbidities, or BMI \u226530 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2 \u003C/sup\u003Ewith obesity-related conditions. This patient\u0027s BMI and lack of comorbidities make surgery inappropriate as initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVery low calorie diet with meal replacements\u003C/strong\u003E can achieve rapid weight loss but requires medical supervision due to potential complications. It is typically reserved for specific medical situations requiring rapid weight loss rather than as first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrict 1200 kcal/day diet\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive and unlikely to achieve sustainable results. Very restrictive diets often lead to poor adherence, nutritional deficiencies, and weight regain. A more moderate approach focusing on healthy eating patterns is more likely to succeed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial management for BMI 30-35 kg/m2 without comorbidities should focus on intensive lifestyle modification with specific, actionable advice.","Bariatric surgery is indicated for BMI \u226535 kg/m2 regardless of comorbidities, or BMI \u226530 kg/m2 with obesity-related conditions.","Weight loss medications should be reserved for BMI \u226530 kg/m2, or BMI \u226527 kg/m2 with obesity-related comorbidities."],"references":["Markovic TP, Proietto J, Dixon JB, Rigas G, Deed G, Hamdorf JM, et al. The australian obesity management algorithm: A simple tool to guide the management of obesity in primary care. Obesity Research \u0026 Clinical Practice. 2022;16(5):353-363. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36050266/","Eisenberg D, Shikora SA, Aarts E, Aminian A, Angrisani L, Cohen RV, et al. 2022 American Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) and International Federation for the Surgery of Obesity and Metabolic Disorders (IFSO): Indications for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery. Surgery for Obesity and Related Diseases [Internet]. 2022 Oct 20;0(0). Available at: https://www.soard.org/article/S1550-7289(22)00641-4/fulltext","Sumithran P, Proietto J. Safe year-long use of a very-low-calorie diet for the treatment of severe obesity. Medical Journal of Australia. 2008 Mar 17;188(6). Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2008/188/6/safe-year-long-use-very-low-calorie-diet-treatment-severe-obesity","Wen LM. It\u0027s time to change the way we think about obesity. Medical Journal of Australia. 2023;208(7):269-270."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"221"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T20:47:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T20:47:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"221"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80765"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta